logical registers, had an impact on the Enlightenment project of thinking politics and economics as a joint enterprise. The volume’s contributors consider politics, economics, and the biological as distinct, semi-autonomous spheres whose various combinations required inventive, sometimes incomplete, acts of conceptual mediation, philosophical negotiation, disciplinary intervention, or aesthetic representation.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Mrz 2022) 0aBiopoliticszEuropexHistory. 0aEconomicszEuropexPhilosophyxHistory. 0aEuropean literaturey18th century. 0aEuropean literaturey19th century. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Semiotics & Theory.2bisacsh1 aBarney, Richard A.1 aBarney, Richard A., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBarney, Richard A., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aCampbell, Timothy C.1 aCampbell, Timothy C., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aChakravorty, Mrinalini, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aChakravorty, Mrinalini.1 aFord, James Edward, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFord, James Edward.1 aGoldstein, Amanda Jo, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGoldstein, Amanda Jo.1 aMacherey, Pierre, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMacherey, Pierre.1 aMann, Annika, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMann, Annika.1 aMarouby, Christian, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMarouby, Christian.1 aMontag, Warren, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMontag, Warren, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aMontag, Warren.1 aPackham, Catherine, econtributor.4c